04731nam a22007695i 9780231520898DE-B159720190708092533.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190708s2009    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315208987 a10.7312/char142302doi  a(DE-B1597)458732  a(OCoLC)778432377  a(OCoLC)979751710  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPR2976 7aLIT0150002bisacsh04a822.331 aCharney, Maurice, eauthor.10aWrinkled Deep in Time :bAging in Shakespeare /cMaurice Charney. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. King Lear, Titus Andronicus, and Cymbeline -- t2. The Aging Pro cess, with Special Reference to Macbeth -- t3. Time the Destroyer in the Sonnets and The Rape of Lucrece -- t4. "Heavy" Fathers -- t5. Politic Old Men: Polonius, Nestor, and Menenius -- t6. Wise Old Men -- t7. Falstaff -- t8. Jealous Old Men: Othello and Leontes -- t9. Old Warriors and Statesmen in the En glish History Plays -- t10. Fatal Attraction: Antony and Cleopatra -- t11. Powerful Older Women -- t12. Loving Older Women -- t13. Lusty Older Women -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aShakespeare was acutely aware of our intimate struggles with aging. His dramatic characters either prosper or suffer according to their relationship with maturity, and his sonnets eloquently explore time's ravaging effects. "Wrinkled deep in time" is how the queen describes herself in Antony and Cleopatra, and at the end of King Lear, there is a tragic sense that both the king and Gloucester have acquired a wisdom they otherwise lacked at the beginning of the play. Even Juliet matures considerably before she drinks Friar Lawrence's potion, and Macbeth and his wife prematurely grow old from their murderous schemes.Drawing on historical documents and the dramatist's own complex depictions, Maurice Charney conducts an original investigation into patterns of aging in Shakespeare, exploring the fulfillment or distress of Shakespeare's characters in combination with their mental and physical decline. Comparing the characterizations of elderly kings and queens, older lovers, patriarchal men, matriarchal women, and the senexthe stereotypical old man of Roman comedywith the history of life expectancy in Shakespeare's England, Charney uncovers similarities and differences between our contemporary attitudes toward aging and aging as it was understood more than four hundred years ago. From this dynamic examination, a new perspective on Shakespeare emerges, one that celebrates and deepens our knowledge of his subtler themes and characters.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aOld age in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066254208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044247208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014z978311045952440uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/char14230423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231520898.jpg  a978-3-11-044247-2  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013  a978-3-11-045952-4  CUP eBook Package Backlist 2000-2014c2000d2014  a978-3-11-066254-2  CUP eBook Package 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG